 Q. (Inaudible.)
 PHIL MICKELSON: I don't know. I don't think so. I think the PGA's done a great job of mixing up their venues. We have had some great historic classic golf courses, Oak Hill was in 2003 and we have played Medinah a few times and they have gone to some classic golf courses as well as modern day courses, so I think that they have mixed it up quite well. 

 Q. (Inaudible.)
 PHIL MICKELSON: We have got great mixture on the TOUR, I think. We have some fun courses like harbor courses that are shorter and tighter and then we have good classic courses like we played last week at Akron and long, brutal modern-day courses like the redesigned Torrey Pines and we seem to have a great mixture. Look at next week at I guess in a week at a couple weeks in Boston, TPC Boston? That's really a fun golf course to play. It doesn't just beat you up in length, but it's got a lot of fun, a drivable par-4, reachable par-5s and some fun holes. I think the TOUR has a good mixture so that it doesn't favor any one particular style of player. 

 Q. Did the questions about the No. 1 ranking do they get old at some point and then the chase for the No. 1 ranking?
 PHIL MICKELSON: No, if I just can get start playing well, yeah, I think that I can get that thing done. But it just wasn't to be this week.

 Q. This round, you had a couple of great stretches there, did you start thinking about maybe delaying your flight if you had gotten to nine or ten but did you think about anything else moving to that the No. 1 ranking if you didn't quite get there because there was some scenarios that might have worked out?
 PHIL MICKELSON: I didn't think about that, no. I told Bones on the 18th hole we said hey, let's give yourself room to the right, you don't want to be here, I said look, I'm not thinking consequences of a bad shot, I was trying to make a three, because I felt like eight might have an outside chance. So that was the last thing I was thinking about was anything other than trying to win a tournament. 

 Q. (Inaudible.)
 PHIL MICKELSON: The only thing I think it has nothing to do with the golf course, I would like to see the walkways for the spectators be easier. Because I think it's the most difficult course to walk. You got great hills and mounds but there's a lot of little holes that prevent people from seeing and it could probably be better viewing and seeing that we're going to have more championships here it would be great to have better spectator viewing. I think it's terrific because it's got great risk reward, it's got, I thought the setup was great, the way they played No. 6 where they moved the tee up twice and moved the pin to the left and then moved it, I thought it was very well done. 

 Q. (Inaudible.)
